@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual -------------------------------------------------- Printing -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Main" "Printing"
@{U}6) Printer support@{UU}

   I implemented the basic printing functions. For portability reasons I chose
to implement my own image rendering routines (I don't use the AMIGA  blitter).
This routines still have some bugs.

   You have to possibility to  choose between different printer drivers.  Cur-
rently available are:

 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}WorkBench Driver@{UB} - This driver will render the image in memory and print
   it to the actual printer as  it is chosen by the WorkBench  preferences.
   Rendering the image uses horrible amounts of memory (DIN A4,  360x360DPI
   needs approx. 11MB for grey and 33MB for color mode!) I implemented some
   @{I}virtual memory @{UI}  management, so be  sure that there  is enough space  on
   your HD.
      I wasn't able to  test this driver correctly,  because my printer  is
   currently @{I}out of order @{UI}. And as mentioned before, the rendering routines
   are not the best.
 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}PostScript Export@{UB} - This will export the image as a PostScript file. You
   have to possibility to process the generated file with an external  com-
   mand. This way you can use e.g. GhostScript to print an image  (avoiding
   my bad routines). Select @{B}Command@{UB} as destination, outputmode  @{B}PostScript@{UB},
   and select from the list a command this:
   @{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} GhostScript:gs <>CON: @stc2.upp -sOutputFile=PAR: -dNOPAUSE %f -c quit
      This will result in a perfect image on my Epson Stylus Color IIs. For
   other printers you will have to change to command. I have to admit  that
   the configuration of GhostScript  is quite difficult... You'll  probably
   have to ask some experienced user.
 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}Amiga Screen@{UB} - Using this driver you  can preview the image on an  AMIGA
   screen. I used it mainly to test my rendering routines.


